        },
        "stable_key": "epub:13:target:epub-text-endnotes.xhtml-note-2"
      },
      {
        "body_html_sanitized": null,
        "body_text": "\u201cTheorie und Praxis,\u201d Zeitsch. des Oesterreichischen Ingenieur u. Architecten-Vereines, 1905, Nr. 4 u. 6. I find a still more radical pragmatism than Ostwald\u2019s in an address by Professor W. S. Franklin: \u201cI think that the sickliest notion of physics, even if a student gets it, is that it is \u2018the science of masses, molecules and the ether.\u2019 And I think that the healthiest notion, even if a student does not wholly get it, is that physics is the science of the ways of taking hold of bodies and pushing them!\u201d (Science, January 2, 1903.) \u21a9\ufe0e",
        "confidence": "exact",
        "extraction_method": "epub_noteref",
        "id": "b3d1f343-87f0-5b19-91e0-cc78184458d8",
        "kind": "endnote",
        "label": "\u201cTheorie",
        "locator": {
